  "prompt": "How common is dying in your sleep?",
  "response": "Dying in one's sleep, often referred to as \"dying peacefully,\" is relatively uncommon but not extremely rare. The frequency depends on various factors such as age, health conditions, and underlying medical issues. Here are some key points:\n\n1. More common in older adults:\n- Elderly people are more likely to die in their sleep\n- Typically due to natural causes like heart failure or respiratory issues\n\n2. Estimated statistics:\n- Approximately 15-20% of deaths occur during sleep\n- More prevalent among people over 65 years old\n\n3. Common causes:\n- Heart attack\n- Stroke\n- Cardiac arrhythmia\n- Sleep apnea\n- Respiratory failure\n\n4. Factors affecting likelihood:\n- Pre-existing health conditions\n- Age\n- Lifestyle habits\n- Genetic predispositions\n\n5. Generally considered a \"peaceful\" way to die:\n- Little to no suffering\n- Typically occurs without the person being aware\n\nWhile dying in one's sleep is not exceedingly common, it is also not extremely rare. The likelihood increases with age and depends on individual health circumstances.\n\nThese are general statistics and should not be considered medical advice. Anyone concerned about their health should consult a healthcare professional.",
